definition.value: A person who uses the pronouns he, they, him, and them in English as their third-person pronouns.
A syndrome with an underlying cause related to the autosome or some larger part of the autosome.
A syndrome with an underlying cause related to the allosome or some larger part of the allosome.
A syndrome with an underlying cause related to a gene or genes that are part of the allosome.
A syndrome with an underlying cause related to a gene or genes that are part of the autosome.
A friend with whom one participates in romantic activities with.
A sexual relationship which is considered casual in nature.
A romantic relationship which is considered casual in nature.
Any of various gender modalities which are considered to be non-cisgender.

label.value: persons by number of pronouns used

definition.value: Individuals classified by number of pronoun or pronouns that they do or do not use.

label.value: persons by type of pronouns used

definition.value: Individuals classified by type of pronoun or pronouns that they do or do not use.

label.value: persons by pronoun use in relationship to gender modality

definition.value: Individuals classified by type of pronoun or pronouns that they do or do not use, and the relationship that those pronouns have to their gender modality.
A cisgender person who uses the pronouns associated with their assigned gender at birth.
A transgender person who uses pronouns not associated with their assigned gender at birth.
A hierarchical polygamous relationship, in which the importance or status of partners is determined via competition.
A polygamous relationship which is hierarchical in nature.

A form of gender nonconformity in which one has a name which is traditionally not associated with their gender; alternatively, a person who does not conform to traditional norms in relationship to their name or names (such as having a mononymous name in a society where most people have a first and last name).
A type of polygamous quadratic relationship which involves two triadic relationships: one in which persons A, B, and C are dating, and a second in which persons B, C, and D are dating.

A person who is gender nonconforming in the sense in which they have a name which is traditionally not associated with their gender; alternatively, a person who does not conform to traditional norms in relationship to their name or names (such as having a mononymous name in a society where most people have a first and last name).
A person who is gender nonconforming in the sense that one uses neopronouns or pronouns in a non-standard manner.
An individual who is nonconforming in terms of some aspect of their behavior, personality, etc.
Rejection of or the failure to conform, especially to standards, rules, or laws.
An individual who does not go by any name; usually by choice.
This term does not include individuals whose names are unknown.
A person whose name is uncommon or nontraditional in relationship to their gender.

A person whose names are uncommon or nontraditional in regard to their number or usage being more numerous than expected; for instance, a person having multiple first names when it is considered more typical to have one.

A person whose singular name is uncommon or nontraditional in regard to their number or usage being less numerous than expected; for instance, a person having one name when it is considered more typical to have more than one.
A person whose pronoun usage is uncommon or nontraditional in relationship to their gender.
A person who uses pronouns specific to a certain location or language.
Love for another in the context of a platonic relationship.
Love for another which is not romantic or sexual in nature.
A rare congenital intersex condition in which an individual with a 46,XX karyotype develops stereotypical phenotypically male characteristics to some degree.
De la Chapelle syndrome in which an individual is SRY positive.
De la Chapelle syndrome in which an individual is SRY negative.
People as organized by karyotype.
An individual with a 46,XX karyotype.
An individual with a 46,XY karyotype.
A man who has a 46,XY karyotype.
A woman who has a 46,XY karyotype.
A man who has a 46,XX karyotype.
A woman who has a 46,XX karyotype.
A part of a dramatic work that is set in the same place or time. In the theatre, generally a number of scenes constitute an act.
A scene that is part of a movie.
A scene that is part of a television episode.
Scenes as organized by type.
Scenes as organized by medium.
A scene in which the two people who will form a future romantic couple meet for the first time, typically under unusual, humorous, or cute circumstances.
Changes or shifts in sexuality over time, usually through processes of self-discovery.
Note that sexual orientation is stable and unchanging for the vast majority of people, and that there is no scientific evidence that sexual orientation can be changed through psychotherapy.
A relationship which is fluid in nature, or a relationship which has changed or will change in nature.
A sexual relationship which is fluid in nature.
